"Abstract In the information systems security community, the process of maintaining integrity has long been understood as the implementation of a set of safeguards against unauthorized modification of information. This point of view, which comes from the military world, is now seriously challenged: integrity could simply be seen as the ability to maintain an acceptable level of quality of information. This article discusses the general concept of quality and gives an overview of the various quality dimensions of information. It then discusses the factors that may ensure and impair the quality of information when it is captured, propagated and used."
